00:07:00.830 --> 00:07:06.486
It is an ethical and often legal mandate
that defines how we should build

00:07:06.545 --> 00:07:07.561
the digital world.

00:07:08.581 --> 00:07:09.811
Why must we start here?

00:07:10.740 --> 00:07:11.740
Because,

00:07:11.880 --> 00:07:14.400
despite the digital evolution,

00:07:14.790 --> 00:07:19.351
despite the fact that we can video call
someone on the other side of the planet,

00:07:19.543 --> 00:07:25.140
access the world's information instantly,
and work from virtually anywhere,

00:07:25.560 --> 00:07:27.270
people with disabilities

00:07:27.901 --> 00:07:32.401
or PWDs continue to face
significant barriers

00:07:33.091 --> 00:07:34.950
in accessing education globally.

00:07:35.761 --> 00:07:38.280
Think about the sheer amount of knowledge,

00:07:38.880 --> 00:07:43.081
training, and opportunities
that are delivered exclusively online.

00:07:43.606 --> 00:07:46.170
Universities have moved courses online.

00:07:47.070 --> 00:07:49.735
Professional certifications are digital.

00:07:50.191 --> 00:07:52.657
Job applications happen
through web portals.

00:07:53.401 --> 00:07:57.630
Freelance marketplaces
operate entirely in the digital space.

00:07:58.111 --> 00:08:01.470
If those pathways
are structurally inaccessible,

00:08:01.771 --> 00:08:06.270
we are systematically excluding
millions of people from obtaining

00:08:06.271 --> 00:08:11.641
the necessary skills to participate fully
in modern society and the economy.

00:08:12.690 --> 00:08:15.811
Let me put this in perspective
with some statistics.

00:08:16.261 --> 00:08:18.751
According
to the World Health Organization,

00:08:19.110 --> 00:08:22.654
approximately 16%
of the global population,

00:08:22.850 --> 00:08:25.170
that's 1.3 billion people,

00:08:25.471 --> 00:08:27.751
experience significant disability.

00:08:28.230 --> 00:08:31.080
In the context of education
and employment,

00:08:31.411 --> 00:08:37.199
studies show that people with disabilities
are significantly less likely to complete

00:08:37.200 --> 00:08:41.819
secondary education and face
unemployment rates that are two

00:08:41.820 --> 00:08:44.761
to three times higher
than those without disabilities.

00:08:45.420 --> 00:08:48.510
Addressing this gap,
this systemic exclusion

00:08:48.511 --> 00:08:54.719
from education, is the first critical step
in ensuring genuine inclusion for persons

00:08:54.720 --> 00:08:55.741
with disabilities,

00:08:56.341 --> 00:08:58.410
but here's the crucial point.

00:08:58.951 --> 00:09:02.670
When we build accessible systems,
everyone benefits.

00:09:02.940 --> 00:09:07.991
Captions help not just deaf users,
but also people watching videos

00:09:08.010 --> 00:09:09.300
in noisy environments,

00:09:09.660 --> 00:09:12.600
or those learning in a second language.

00:09:13.140 --> 00:09:17.791
Keyboard navigation helps not just users
with motor disabilities,

00:09:18.120 --> 00:09:22.800
but also power users who want
to work more efficiently.

00:09:23.520 --> 00:09:26.820
Clear, simple language
helps not just users

00:09:26.881 --> 00:09:30.630
with cognitive disabilities,
but everyone trying to understand

00:09:30.631 --> 00:09:31.861
complex information.

00:09:32.371 --> 00:09:35.970
Accessibility is good design,
it's universal design,

00:09:36.031 --> 00:09:38.340
and it's simply the right thing to do.

00:09:40.721 --> 00:09:46.269
The digital divide for persons
with disabilities is created

00:09:46.270 --> 00:09:51.881
by a combination of technical failure
and social exclusion.

00:09:52.810 --> 00:09:54.960
The challenges we currently face

00:09:55.010 --> 00:09:58.871
can be distilled
into four critical barriers,

00:09:59.231 --> 00:10:05.050
but I want to spend time really unpacking
each one so you can understand

00:10:05.051 --> 00:10:09.251
the lived reality
behind these technical descriptions.

00:10:10.180 --> 00:10:11.180
Firstly,

00:10:11.261 --> 00:10:15.311
we contend
with inaccessible platforms and tools.

00:10:15.791 --> 00:10:18.911
Many mainstream learning
management systems,

00:10:19.101 --> 00:10:20.501
collaboration tools,

00:10:20.921 --> 00:10:25.931
and general software are designed
without disabled users in mind.

00:10:26.441 --> 00:10:30.220
This means navigation
is impossible for some,

00:10:30.521 --> 00:10:36.337
or essential functions are unusable,
locking out individuals

00:10:36.551 --> 00:10:38.680
before they even begin to learn.

00:10:39.460 --> 00:10:42.401
Let me give you a concrete example.

00:10:42.790 --> 00:10:47.801
Imagine you're a blind student
trying to enroll in an online course.

00:10:48.131 --> 00:10:51.790
You navigate to the website
using your screen reader,

00:10:52.120 --> 00:10:55.901
software that reads the test
on screen aloud to you,

00:10:57.221 --> 00:11:02.441
but the course registration form
wasn't coded with accessibility in mind.

00:11:02.860 --> 00:11:07.810
The form fields don't have proper labels,
so your screen reader just says,

00:11:08.170 --> 00:11:09.170
edit books,

00:11:09.490 --> 00:11:12.783
without telling you
what information to put there.

00:11:13.271 --> 00:11:18.401
The submit button is actually
an image without an alternative test,

00:11:18.761 --> 00:11:24.071
so you don't even know
where to click to submit your form.

00:11:25.090 --> 00:11:28.691
The course you want
to take might be perfect for you,

00:11:28.930 --> 00:11:33.185
but you can't even register
because the gateway is locked.

00:11:33.941 --> 00:11:39.251
This isn't a hypothetical scenario,
this happens every single day

00:11:39.460 --> 00:11:43.541
to millions of people
trying to access education,

00:11:43.781 --> 00:11:46.720
employment, and essential services online.

00:11:48.190 --> 00:11:53.050
Secondly, there is
the pervasive issue of training content

00:11:53.051 --> 00:11:54.370
without captions.

00:11:55.062 --> 00:11:58.300
While captions
might seem like a small detail to those

00:11:58.300 --> 00:11:59.651
who don't rely on them,

00:12:00.191 --> 00:12:04.451
the lack of them instantly renders
educational videos,

00:12:04.811 --> 00:12:08.134
lectures,
and virtual training inaccessible

00:12:08.500 --> 00:12:12.221
to individuals who are deaf
or hard of hearing.

00:12:12.940 --> 00:12:17.590
This exclusion narrows
the available educational contents

00:12:17.680 --> 00:12:18.700
dramatically.

00:12:21.041 --> 00:12:23.950
Consider the explosion
of video-based learning.

00:12:25.211 --> 00:12:26.980
Platforms like YouTube,

00:12:27.370 --> 00:12:32.531
Coursera, and Udemy have democratized
education in many ways.

00:12:32.950 --> 00:12:37.810
You can learn almost anything
from world-class instructors,

00:12:38.590 --> 00:12:43.781
but if you are deaf or hard of hearing
and the video doesn't have captions,

00:12:44.051 --> 00:12:47.230
that entire course is closed to you.

00:12:47.860 --> 00:12:51.041
You might be the most motivated learner
in the world,

00:12:51.340 --> 00:12:56.261
but motivation can't overcome
a fundamental technical barrier.

00:12:57.985 --> 00:13:02.561
Here's what frustrates me most
about this particular barrier.

00:13:03.040 --> 00:13:06.160
Adding captions is entirely achievable.

00:13:06.549 --> 00:13:08.170
The technology exists.

00:13:08.590 --> 00:13:11.980
Automatic captioning
has improved dramatically.

00:13:12.461 --> 00:13:15.371
Manual captioning services are affordable.

00:13:15.760 --> 00:13:19.121
The barrier here
isn't technical impossibility,

00:13:19.510 --> 00:13:21.250
it's lack of awareness,

00:13:21.551 --> 00:13:25.121
lack of priority,
and sometimes lack of care.

00:13:27.075 --> 00:13:30.988
Thirdly, we often see a fundamental lack
of assistive technology support.

00:13:31.391 --> 00:13:38.051
Assistive technologies
such as screen readers for blind users,

00:13:38.381 --> 00:13:42.100
voice recognition software
for those with motor disabilities,

00:13:42.430 --> 00:13:47.632
or switch control for users
with limited mobility are essential tools.

00:13:48.100 --> 00:13:52.781
When platforms are poorly coded,
they conflict with these tools,

00:13:53.051 --> 00:13:55.150
rendering technology useless.

00:13:57.731 --> 00:14:01.061
If a screen reader
cannot correctly interpret

00:14:01.421 --> 00:14:02.711
a website structure,

00:14:02.981 --> 00:14:06.394
that website remains closed off.

00:14:06.881 --> 00:14:12.189
This barrier is particularly insidious
because it's often invincible

00:14:12.190 --> 00:14:16.090
to developers who don't use
assistive technology themselves.

00:14:16.661 --> 00:14:20.710
A website might look perfectly functional
in a standard browser,

00:14:21.101 --> 00:14:24.280
but be completely unusable
with a screen reader.

00:14:24.730 --> 00:14:28.660
Developers might use
the latest JavaScript framework and create

00:14:28.673 --> 00:14:33.520
beautiful animations,
but if they don't consider

00:14:33.521 --> 00:14:40.240
semantic HTML or keyboard navigations,
they've built a beautiful building

00:14:40.270 --> 00:14:41.290
with no doors.

00:14:42.671 --> 00:14:45.041
I want to emphasize
something important here.

00:14:45.400 --> 00:14:47.111
Assistive technology users

00:14:48.460 --> 00:14:50.591
incredibly resourceful and determined.

00:14:50.613 --> 00:14:54.521
They will try workarounds,
they will spend extra hours

00:14:54.701 --> 00:14:57.550
trying to make something work,
they will seek help

00:14:57.671 --> 00:14:58.990
from their networks,

00:14:59.290 --> 00:15:03.820
but the burden should not be on them
to constantly adapt to our failures.

00:15:04.240 --> 00:15:09.790
The burden should be on us as creators
to build right from the start.

00:15:11.621 --> 00:15:16.421
Finally and critically,
there's limited community support.

00:15:17.021 --> 00:15:21.371
Technical barriers are often compounded
by social isolation.

00:15:21.881 --> 00:15:25.780
When persons with disabilities
pursue technical training,

00:15:26.146 --> 00:15:34.420
they need not only technical resources,
but a strong supportive peer network

00:15:34.690 --> 00:15:38.170
where they can share
challenges, find mentorship,

00:15:38.411 --> 00:15:39.971
and feel represented.

00:15:40.540 --> 00:15:46.751
A lack of this community support can lead
to attrition and limit long-term success.

00:15:47.561 --> 00:15:51.520
Think about your own learning journey,
whether you learned to code,

00:15:51.850 --> 00:15:54.820
learned a new language,
or developed a new skill.

00:15:55.090 --> 00:15:56.090
Who helped you?

00:15:56.650 --> 00:16:00.161
Maybe it was a friend
who recommended a good resource.

00:16:00.520 --> 00:16:04.450
Maybe it was a study group
that kept you motivated.

00:16:04.841 --> 00:16:09.460
Maybe it was a mentor who believed in you
when you doubted yourself.

00:16:09.880 --> 00:16:13.927
Maybe it was just seeing someone
who looked like you succeeding

00:16:13.928 --> 00:16:17.111
in that field and thinking
if they can do it too,

00:16:17.320 --> 00:16:18.320
so can I.

00:16:19.331 --> 00:16:22.991
Now imagine trying to break
into the tech industry,

00:16:23.380 --> 00:16:29.020
an industry already known for
being exclusive and sometimes unwelcoming,

00:16:29.621 --> 00:16:32.321
without any of those support structures.

00:16:32.651 --> 00:16:37.718
Imagine being one of the only people
with a disability in your course,

00:16:37.878 --> 00:16:40.151
in your boot camp, in a workplace.

00:16:40.450 --> 00:16:46.240
Imagine not having anyone who understands
the specific challenges you face

00:16:46.450 --> 00:16:51.611
or who can give you advice
that actually applies to your situation.

00:16:52.211 --> 00:16:55.331
This isolation doesn't just make
the journey harder,

00:16:55.631 --> 00:16:59.621
it makes people give up entirely,
and when that happens,

00:16:59.910 --> 00:17:00.970
we all lose.

00:17:01.211 --> 00:17:04.331
We lose their perspective,
their creativity,

00:17:04.331 --> 00:17:07.840
their contributions,
and their potential leadership.

00:17:10.540 --> 00:17:15.670
While the challenges are formidable,
the opportunity to transform lives

00:17:15.940 --> 00:17:19.240
through inclusive training
is even greater.

00:17:19.571 --> 00:17:23.771
By intentionally designing
training programs for accessibility,

00:17:24.010 --> 00:17:26.141
we unlock profound benefits,

00:17:26.470 --> 00:17:28.420
not just for the participants,

00:17:28.930 --> 00:17:31.120
but for society as a whole.

00:17:31.661 --> 00:17:36.580
I want to shift our mindset here
from seeing accessibility as a problem

00:17:36.581 --> 00:17:40.480
to solve, to seeing it
as an opportunity to seize.

00:17:40.781 --> 00:17:44.920
Because when we get this right,
the benefits ripple out

00:17:44.921 --> 00:17:47.800
