personally through our program.

00:20:35.800 --> 00:20:37.241
Participants who entered

00:20:37.841 --> 00:20:41.679
uncertain about their prospects,
who had been told explicitly

00:20:41.680 --> 00:20:42.731
or implicitly

00:20:44.220 --> 00:20:46.631
that certain careers weren't for them,

00:20:47.201 --> 00:20:50.669
who had internalized
society's low expectations,

00:20:50.893 --> 00:20:54.460
these same participants now run
their own freelance businesses,

00:20:54.762 --> 00:20:58.091
earn competitive salaries,
and more importantly,

00:20:58.181 --> 00:21:02.050
see themselves as valuable contributions
to the digital economy.

00:21:02.710 --> 00:21:07.366
That shift in self-perception from,
I need help, to,

00:21:07.438 --> 00:21:12.611
I have valuable skills to offer,
that's the shift that changes everything.

00:21:14.561 --> 00:21:18.970
Thirdly, we achieve
digital participation and representation.

00:21:19.391 --> 00:21:25.270
When people with disabilities are skilled
and employed in the digital economy,

00:21:25.631 --> 00:21:28.566
they cease being mere consumers
of technology

00:21:28.616 --> 00:21:31.150
and become creators and shapers of it.

00:21:31.492 --> 00:21:36.820
Their perspectives are essential
for building truly inclusive products,

00:21:37.180 --> 00:21:41.711
thereby increasing representation
across the tech landscape.

00:21:42.490 --> 00:21:45.310
Here's a hard truth
about the tech industry,

00:21:45.641 --> 00:21:47.620
we have a diversity problem.

00:21:47.948 --> 00:21:53.050
The people building our digital future
don't represent the diversity of people

00:21:53.051 --> 00:21:53.881
who use it,

00:21:53.981 --> 00:21:57.010
and when the builders aren't diverse,

00:21:57.190 --> 00:22:01.240
the products reflect the lack
of diversity through oversight,

00:22:01.351 --> 00:22:04.982
through bias,
and through outright exclusion.

00:22:06.070 --> 00:22:07.481
Here's the opportunity,

00:22:07.810 --> 00:22:11.441
when we bring people with disability
into tech as designers,

00:22:11.680 --> 00:22:14.726
developers, product managers,
and leaders,

00:22:14.806 --> 00:22:17.021
they bring invaluable perspective.

00:22:17.580 --> 00:22:21.205
They understand accessibility not
as a compliance checkbox,

00:22:21.640 --> 00:22:24.701
but as a fundamental design principle.

00:22:25.030 --> 00:22:27.181
They catch issues that others miss.

00:22:27.400 --> 00:22:30.370
They advocate for inclusive features
from the beginning

00:22:30.370 --> 00:22:31.870
of the development process,

00:22:32.170 --> 00:22:33.581
not as an afterthought.

00:22:34.450 --> 00:22:39.491
Beyond the practical benefits,
representation matters for its own sake.

00:22:39.670 --> 00:22:44.839
When a young person with a disability
sees someone like them succeeding in tech,

00:22:44.981 --> 00:22:47.770
it expands their sense of what's possible.

00:22:48.011 --> 00:22:52.031
It challenges stereotypes,
it changes narratives,

00:22:52.241 --> 00:22:54.670
it inspires the next generation.

00:22:56.770 --> 00:23:00.731
Finally, we build empowered communities.

00:23:01.301 --> 00:23:04.420
When individuals gain
skills and confidence,

00:23:04.780 --> 00:23:09.431
they often turn around and lift up those
in their networks,

00:23:09.640 --> 00:23:14.261
creating a powerful ripple effect
that strengthens social cohesion

00:23:14.621 --> 00:23:17.831
and spreads a culture of inclusion.

00:23:18.941 --> 00:23:22.611
One of the most beautiful things
I've observed in our program

00:23:22.612 --> 00:23:27.370
is how quickly participants
go from being learners to teachers.

00:23:28.120 --> 00:23:30.969
Someone who struggled
with their concept three weeks

00:23:30.970 --> 00:23:35.051
ago is now helping
a newer participant understand it.

00:23:35.440 --> 00:23:38.290
Someone who landed
their first freelance client

00:23:39.401 --> 00:23:43.390
is now sharing advice with others
on how to find opportunities.

00:23:43.750 --> 00:23:46.751
Someone who built
their first accessible website

00:23:46.991 --> 00:23:50.321
is now advocating for accessibility
in their community.

00:23:51.761 --> 00:23:56.362
This is how movements grow,
not through top-down mandates,

00:23:56.452 --> 00:24:01.751
but through grassroots empowerment
where each person actually succeeds,

00:24:02.021 --> 00:24:04.900
reaches back to help
the next person climb up.

00:24:05.260 --> 00:24:08.500
This creates sustainable change
that doesn't depend

00:24:08.501 --> 00:24:11.650
on any single organization or initiative,

00:24:12.161 --> 00:24:16.780
but becomes woven
into the fabric of the community itself.

00:24:18.371 --> 00:24:22.481
So, the problem is clear
and the potential is huge,

00:24:22.871 --> 00:24:24.791
but how do we bridge that gap?

00:24:25.090 --> 00:24:27.010
This is where open source comes in.

00:24:27.431 --> 00:24:32.589
I firmly believe that open source
democratizes access to technology

00:24:32.590 --> 00:24:34.121
and learning opportunities.

00:24:34.600 --> 00:24:37.571
Tools like WordPress are perfect examples.

00:24:37.861 --> 00:24:41.650
WordPress is open source,
meaning it's free to use,

00:24:41.830 --> 00:24:43.660
modify and distribute.

00:24:43.991 --> 00:24:48.460
This removes the financial barrier
to entry that proprietary software

00:24:48.461 --> 00:24:49.581
often creates.

00:24:49.582 --> 00:24:54.460
It has a massive global community
dedicated to its development and support,

00:24:54.820 --> 00:25:00.429
including a very active accessibility team
committing to making the platform usable

00:25:00.430 --> 00:25:01.430
for everyone.

00:25:04.301 --> 00:25:08.860
This belief in the power of open source
and community led

00:25:08.861 --> 00:25:10.367
to the creation of TechAble.

00:25:10.757 --> 00:25:16.450
TechAble is an initiative that aims
to bridge the technological gap for people

00:25:16.451 --> 00:25:17.651
with disabilities.

00:25:17.880 --> 00:25:22.155
Our mission is to enhance employability,
promote inclusivity

00:25:22.205 --> 00:25:26.920
in the digital economy by providing
accessible digital skills training

00:25:27.310 --> 00:25:29.561
in web development using WordPress.

00:25:29.950 --> 00:25:34.690
We set out to create a program
that didn't just teach technical skills,

00:25:34.931 --> 00:25:38.530
but also address
the other barriers we identified.

00:25:38.861 --> 00:25:43.060
We wanted to build a supportive,
inclusive environment where people

00:25:43.061 --> 00:25:44.351
could not only learn,

00:25:44.621 --> 00:25:48.281
but also thrive and feel
a true sense of belonging.

00:25:50.561 --> 00:25:53.865
A crucial component
of the TechAble mission

00:25:54.045 --> 00:25:57.310
is a specific focus on gender inclusion.

00:25:57.821 --> 00:26:03.610
Statistics often show that women,
and particularly women with disabilities,

00:26:03.821 --> 00:26:07.180
face a double barrier
to entry in the tech sector.

00:26:07.661 --> 00:26:10.300
We are actively working
to change that narrative.

00:26:10.840 --> 00:26:15.156
Let me provide some context
for why this focus is so important.

00:26:15.760 --> 00:26:18.970
Women are already underrepresented
in tech globally,

00:26:19.360 --> 00:26:24.760
typically comprising only about 25%
to 30% of the tech workforce.

00:26:25.180 --> 00:26:28.300
Women with disabilities
face even steeper odds,

00:26:28.690 --> 00:26:32.860
dealing with both gender discrimination
and disability discrimination,

00:26:33.730 --> 00:26:37.061
what researchers
call intersectional disadvantage.

00:26:37.450 --> 00:26:41.020
Studies have shown that women
with disabilities experience

00:26:41.351 --> 00:26:47.259
lower employment rates than both men
with disabilities and women

00:26:47.260 --> 00:26:50.651
without disabilities,
higher rates of poverty,

00:26:50.920 --> 00:26:55.331
less access to education,
more significant wage gaps,

00:26:55.601 --> 00:26:57.911
greater barriers to career advancement.

00:26:59.110 --> 00:27:03.280
We decided that addressing
this intersectional challenge would be

00:27:03.281 --> 00:27:06.331
a core focus of TechAble,
not an afterthought.

00:27:06.621 --> 00:27:11.051
I am proud to share
that 56% of our participants are women.

00:27:11.411 --> 00:27:13.960
This demonstrates
our commitment to providing

00:27:15.011 --> 00:27:18.700
an equitable environment
where everyone has a chance to thrive.

00:27:19.301 --> 00:27:21.982
We didn't achieve
this percentage by accident.

00:27:22.211 --> 00:27:26.621
It required intentional outreach,
creating a supportive environment,

00:27:26.860 --> 00:27:29.980
addressing specific barriers
and being thoughtful

00:27:29.981 --> 00:27:31.631
about the program design.

00:27:35.861 --> 00:27:40.359
Our program's overarching goal is
that it empowers women to shape

00:27:40.360 --> 00:27:42.310
accessible digital futures.

00:27:42.701 --> 00:27:48.670
When we invest in them, we not only change
individual lives but also ensure

00:27:48.671 --> 00:27:51.854
that the future generation
of digital products

00:27:51.884 --> 00:27:56.051
and services is designed
with a wider, more inclusive lens.

00:27:56.500 --> 00:27:59.381
The women in our program
are not just learning to code,

00:27:59.680 --> 00:28:00.980
they are learning to lead.

00:28:01.240 --> 00:28:04.360
They are becoming
the next generation of tech entrepreneurs,

00:28:04.600 --> 00:28:07.630
accessibility advocates
and community builders,

00:28:07.930 --> 00:28:11.650
and that's going to change
the face of tech in Ghana and beyond.

00:28:13.690 --> 00:28:18.520
A core component of TechAble's success
is our approach to mentorship.

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:22.961
We knew that just providing
lessons wouldn't be enough.

00:28:23.290 --> 00:28:27.776
We needed to address the issue
of limited community support head-on.

00:28:28.126 --> 00:28:32.381
Our mentorship program
provides personalized guidance.

00:28:32.901 --> 00:28:35.771
Each participant is paired
with experienced mentors

00:28:35.771 --> 00:28:39.611
from the tech industry
who can provide one-on-one support,

00:28:39.764 --> 00:28:43.120
answer technical questions
and offer career advice.

00:28:44.341 --> 00:28:46.271
It fosters peer support.

00:28:46.571 --> 00:28:51.550
We built a community where participants
can learn from and support each other.

00:28:51.851 --> 00:28:53.620
They work on projects together,

00:28:53.830 --> 00:28:58.091
share their challenges and successes
and build lasting friendships.

00:28:58.451 --> 00:29:03.430
This peer network is often just
as valuable as the formal training itself,

00:29:03.990 --> 00:29:05.021
and crucially,

00:29:05.291 --> 00:29:09.010
it helps participants build
valuable industry networks.

00:29:09.340 --> 00:29:12.370
Our mentors open doors
for our participants,

00:29:12.611 --> 00:29:16.270
connecting them to people
and opportunities they might not

00:29:16.271 --> 00:29:17.680
otherwise have access to.

00:29:18.221 --> 00:29:22.420
This helps to break down
the professional barriers that can be just

00:29:22.421 --> 00:29:24.611
as challenging as the technical ones.

00:29:28.181 --> 00:29:29.711
What has the impact been?

00:29:30.071 --> 00:29:31.481
It has been profound,

00:29:31.870 --> 00:29:35.471
both for the individuals
and for the community as a whole.

00:29:35.741 --> 00:29:37.001
First and foremost,

00:29:37.181 --> 00:29:40.331
participants built
their first accessible websites.

00:29:40.601 --> 00:29:44.290
They went from having little
or no web development experience

00:29:44.621 --> 00:29:47.260
to creating fully functional,
professional,

00:29:47.440 --> 00:29:50.620
and most importantly, accessible websites.

00:29:50.951 --> 00:29:53.440
This is a huge technical achievement.

00:29:54.251 --> 00:29:57.341
Perhaps even more important
is the human impact.

00:29:57.641 --> 00:30:02.681
We saw participants gain the confidence
to pursue freelance and digital jobs.

00:30:02.880 --> 00:30:05.394
They started to see
themselves as professionals,

00:30:05.701 --> 00:30:07.920
as people with valuable skills to offer.

00:30:08.310 --> 00:30:11.070
That shift in mindset is life-changing.

00:30:11.730 --> 00:30:15.059
Finally, we fostered
a stronger sense of community

00:30:15.060 --> 00:30:16.060
and inclusion.

00:30:16.201 --> 00:30:20.521
Participants told us they finally felt
they belong in the tech world.

00:30:20.880 --> 00:30:25.590
They found a network of peers and mentors
who understood them and supported them.

00:30:25.980 --> 00:30:29.250
This sense of belonging is
the foundation upon

00:30:29.281 --> 00:30:31.471
which long-term success is built.

00:30:34.411 --> 00:30:39.781
No initiative succeeds without challenges
and no team grows without learning

00:30:39.811 --> 00:30:40.860
from mistakes.

00:30:42.151 --> 00:30:45.630
One first major lesson
was that accessibility

00:30:45.631 --> 00:30:49.531
is not something you achieve once
and check off your list.

00:30:49.801 --> 00:30:53.251
It's an ongoing commitment
that requires constant attention,

00:30:53.611 --> 00:30:55.350
learning, and improvement.

00:30:58.921 --> 00:31:03.391
Our second major lesson was
about the diversity of disabilities

00:31:03.451 --> 00:31:04.740
and learning styles.

00:31:05.401 --> 00:31:09.061
Different disabilities require
different accommodations.

00:31:09.570 --> 00:31:12.989
What works for deaf participants
doesn't necessarily work

00:31:12.990 --> 00:31:14.581
for a blind participant.

00:31:18.570 --> 00:31:22.080
Beyond disability categories,
people are individuals

00:31:22.081 --> 00:31:25.174
with different learning paces,
different prior knowledge

00:31:25.254 --> 00:31:26.800
and different goals.

00:31:32.070 --> 00:31:36.511
Lesson 3, soft skills
matter as much as technical ones.

00:31:36.931 --> 00:31:39.840
Technical skills are necessary
but not sufficient.

00:31:40.171 --> 00:31:44.311
Many of our graduates struggle not
because they couldn't build good websites

00:31:44.611 --> 00:31:47.101
but because they didn't know
how to find clients,

00:31:47.461 --> 00:31:48.841
communicate professionally,

00:31:48.961 --> 00:31:52.471
price their services, manage
projects or market themselves.

00:31:55.200 --> 00:31:58.140
Lesson 4,
perhaps our most important lesson,

00:31:58.411 --> 00:32:02.551
has been about the psychological
and emotional dimensions of this work.

00:32:03.511 --> 00:32:07.321
Many of our participants entered
the program carrying years of rejection,

00:32:07.711 --> 00:32:11.850
low expectations from others
and internalized ableism.

00:32:12.351 --> 00:32:18.514
They've been told explicitly or implicitly
that they can't succeed in tech.

00:32:18.934 --> 00:32:21.361
Some have been discouraged
by family members

00:32:21.751 --> 00:32:26.971
out of misguided protectiveness try
to steer them toward more realistic goals.

00:32:29.241 --> 00:32:33.241
Technical training alone doesn't overcome
years of being told you're not capable.

00:32:33.361 --> 00:32:36.210
We learned that we needed
to intentionally address

00:32:36.211 --> 00:32:39.990
the psychological barriers alongside
the technical ones.

00:32:42.690 --> 00:32:46.801
Lesson 5, partnership and collaboration

00:32:47.341 --> 00:32:48.721
amplify impact.

00:32:53.820 --> 00:32:57.420
We've learned that collaboration,
not competition,

00:32:57.510 --> 00:32:59.551
is how social impact works best.

00:33:00.151 --> 00:33:03.930
When organizations working
towards similar goals support each other,

00:33:04.380 --> 00:33:05.521
everyone wins,

00:33:05.700 --> 00:33:08.969
especially
the people we are all trying to serve.

00:33:10.531 --> 00:33:13.801
We've covered a lot of ground
in this presentation.

00:33:14.221 --> 00:33:17.250
Now I want to talk
about the most important part,

00:33:17.550 --> 00:33:19.951
what you can do
to help advance this mission.

00:33:20.370 --> 00:33:22.650
There are actions you can take right now

00:33:22.700 --> 00:33:26.160
regardless of your role or resources.

00:33:26.250 --> 00:33:28.170
Let me suggest several ways you can.

00:33:29.221 --> 00:33:33.120
For developers and designers,
learn accessibility standards.

00:33:33.451 --> 00:33:36.451
There are
excellent free resources available online.

00:33:37.440 --> 00:33:40.361
If you have
accessibility expertise, share it.

00:33:40.710 --> 00:33:42.390
Mentor someone who is learning.

00:33:43.261 --> 00:33:48.090
For employers and business leaders,
don't just say you value diversity.

00:33:48.517 --> 00:33:50.130
Demonstrate it through action.

00:33:50.491 --> 00:33:53.071
Actively recruit people with disabilities.

00:33:55.831 --> 00:33:59.880
For educators and trainers,
make your content accessible.

00:34:00.151 --> 00:34:02.371
Use accessible documents formats.

00:34:02.640 --> 00:34:05.581
Test your learning platforms
with assistive technology.

00:34:08.491 --> 00:34:10.860
For funders and philanthropists,

00:34:11.400 --> 00:34:15.661
support programs that are doing
the hard work of creating opportunity.

00:34:16.080 --> 00:34:19.501
Accessible training programs
need financial support to scale.

00:34:20.791 --> 00:34:25.561
For advocates and allies, learn
about accessibility and disability rights.

00:34:25.860 --> 00:34:28.320
Read blogs by people with disabilities.

00:34:28.891 --> 00:34:31.534
Speak up when you encounter
inaccessible products

00:34:31.535 --> 00:34:33.480
or discriminatory practices.

00:34:34.141 --> 00:34:36.960
Support disability-led organizations.

00:34:37.320 --> 00:34:39.300
For people with disabilities,

00:34:40.201 --> 00:34:41.201
know your worth.

00:34:41.461 --> 00:34:45.211
You have valuable skills,
perspectives and contributions to offer.

00:34:45.571 --> 00:34:50.640
The barriers you face are not your fault
and they do not reflect your abilities.

00:34:51.031 --> 00:34:53.490
Connect with other people
with disabilities.

00:34:53.760 --> 00:34:56.850
Share resources, challenges and successes.

00:34:57.157 --> 00:34:58.920
There is power in community.

00:35:00.061 --> 00:35:01.561
Advocate for yourself.

00:35:01.921 --> 00:35:06.481
Learn to articulate your needs
and advocate for accommodations.

00:35:08.580 --> 00:35:09.840
Consider mentoring.

00:35:10.291 --> 00:35:15.061
Once you have the skills and experience,
consider paying it forward.

00:35:16.260 --> 00:35:18.601
I'll leave you
with one specific challenge.

00:35:18.930 --> 00:35:23.940
In the next week, take one concrete action
to advance digital accessibility.

